### Collection If

The `if` inside a collection literal conditionally includes elements.

```dart
void main() {
  bool includeExtra = true;

  var items = [
    'apple',
    'banana',
    if (includeExtra) 'orange',
  ];

  print(items); // [apple, banana, orange]

  includeExtra = false;

  var items2 = [
    'apple',
    'banana',
    if (includeExtra) 'orange',
  ];

  print(items2); // [apple, banana]
}
```

### Collection If-Else

Dart 3.0+ supports `if-else` inside collection literals.

```dart
void main() {
  bool isPremium = true;

  var features = [
    'basic_feature',
    if (isPremium)
      'premium_feature'
    else
      'ad_supported',
  ];

  print(features); // [basic_feature, premium_feature]

  // Multiple conditions
  var userType = 'admin';
  var permissions = [
    'read',
    if (userType == 'admin') 'write' else 'write_limited',
    if (userType == 'admin') 'delete',
  ];

  print(permissions); // [read, write, delete]
}
```

### Collection For

The `for` inside a collection literal iterates and includes elements.

```dart
void main() {
  var numbers = [1, 2, 3];

  var doubled = [
    for (var n in numbers) n * 2,
  ];

  print(doubled); // [2, 4, 6]

  // Multiple elements per iteration
  var expanded = [
    for (var n in numbers)
      if (n.isOdd) ...[n, n * 10],
  ];

  print(expanded); // [1, 10, 3, 30]
}
```

### Combining If and For

```dart
void main() {
  bool showEven = true;
  var numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6];

  var result = [
    for (var n in numbers)
      if (showEven ? n.isEven : n.isOdd)
        n * 10,
  ];

  print(result); // [20, 40, 60]
}
```

### Practical Example

```dart
List<String> generateMenu(bool isLoggedIn, List<String> items) {
  return [
    'home',
    'about',
    if (isLoggedIn) ...[
      'profile',
      'settings',
      'logout',
    ] else
      'login',
    for (var item in items) item,
  ];
}

void main() {
  print(generateMenu(true, ['shop', 'cart']));
  print(generateMenu(false, ['shop', 'cart']));
}
```

> **Key Point:** Collection `if` and `for` enable declarative list building without temporary variables. They work in List, Set, and Map literals.

